on/so-trist.htm|title=South Africa: Tristan Da Cunha|date=March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426191925/http://www.globalbioclimatics.org/station/so-trist.htm#|archive-date=26 April 2015|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|source 2 = Climate and Temperature<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.climatetemp.info/tristan-da-cunha/ |title=Tristan Da Cunha Climate Guide to the Average Weather & Temperatures with Graphs Elucidating Sunshine and Rainfall Data & Information about Wind Speeds & Humidity |date=March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111117211803/http://www.climatetemp.info/tristan-da-cunha/ |archivedate=17 November 2011 }}</ref><ref>http://www.tristandc.com/wildclimate.php</ref>\n\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n\n{{climate chart|Edinburgh of the Seven Seas\n|16|20|93\n|17|21|113\n|16|20|121\n|15|18|129\n|13|17|155\n|11|15|160\n|11|14|160\n|10|14|175\n|10|14|169\n|11|15|151\n|13|17|128\n|15|19|127\n|float=right\n|source=[http://www.climatetemp.info/tristan-da-cunha/ Climate and Temperature Information]\n}}\n\n==Transport==\nThere is one road, M1, which connects the town with Patches and is used by the few private cars on the island.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristandc.com/visitsexcursions.php|title=Tristan da Cunha Visitor Excursions|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref> Paved paths provide walking access to buildings around town. A bus service called Potato Patches Flier (using a 24-seat Isuzu mini school bus from South Africa<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristantimes.com/art_4512_56_8_1.html|title=The Tristan Times Newspaper \u2013 News from Tristan da Cunha|accessdate=30 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031101436/http://www.tristantimes.com/art_4512_56_8_1.html|archive-date=31 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>) is available to pensioners in town to travel to places around the island.<ref name=\"tristandc.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tristandc.com/newstransport.php|title=Tristan da Cunha Land Transport News|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAll motor vehicles on the island have Tristan da Cunha plates consisting of letters TDC and 2 or 3 numbers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olavsplates.com/tristan_da_cunha_abroad.html|title=Olav's Tristanian number plates \u2013 Photographed in Tristan da Cunha|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe town has a small harbour with berths accessible by small vessels only.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Edinburgh-Tristan.jpg|\nFile:Edinburgh of the Seven Seas 01.jpg|\nFile:Edinburgh of the Seven Seas 03.jpg|\n</gallery>\n\n==Art==\nGraphic artist [[Rolf Weijburg]] produced an etch of Edinburgh of the Seven Seas<ref>http://www.weijburg.nl/portofolio/etsen/116v.jpg </ref> and other places on the island of [[Tristan da Cunha]].<ref>Rolf Weijburg\u2019s website: http://www.weijburg.nl</ref>\n\n==Local government==\nThe island's local affairs are managed by the Island Council, a 14-member administration that meets six times a year and is elected every three years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://capital.osd.wednet.edu/media/capital/library/pdf/tristan_da_cunha.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=15 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114222251/http://capital.osd.wednet.edu/media/capital/library/pdf/tristan_da_cunha.pdf |archive-date=14 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Government services==\nThe town is home to the island's emergency services, which comprise one ambulance (a [[Toyota Hilux]] operated by Camogli Hospital), one fire engine (a [[Land Rover Defender]] with a small ladder) and one police car ([[Land Rover Series]]).<ref name=\"tristandc.com\"/>\n\nThe town administration also has a vehicle for official use.<ref name=\"tristandc.com\"/>\n\n==Places of interest and attractions==\nMost buildings in town are single story, with the largest being the factory and the tallest being St Joseph's Church.\n\n* St Mary's Anglican Church \u2013 built 1923<ref name=\"tristandc.com1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tristandc.com/churches.php|title=Tristan Churches|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>\n* [[St. Joseph Church, Edinburgh of the Seven Seas|St. Joseph Catholic Church]] \u2013 built 1995\u201396 and replaced earlier church from 1983<ref name=\"tristandc.com1\"/>\n* St Mary's School \u2013 built 1975<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristandc.com/school.php|title=Tristan School|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>\n* Camogli Hospital \u2013 built in 1971 to replace Station Hospital (c. 1940s)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristandc.com/hospital.php|title=Camogli Hospital Tristan da Cunha|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>\n* Calshot Harbour \u2013 built 1967<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristandc.com/harbour.php|title=Tristan da Cunha's Calshot Harbour|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>\n* Prince Philip Hall and the Albatross Bar\n* Tristan Thatched House Museum\n* Agriculture Department warehouse\n* Tristan Island Store \u2013 only supermarket on the island<ref name=\"tristandc.com2\">http://www.tristandc.com/shops.php</ref>\n* Tristan Post Office, Tourism Centre and Caf\u00e9 da Cunha \u2013 opened 2009<ref name=\"tristandc.com2\"/>\n* Administration Building \u2013 home to Island Council\n* Crayfish Canning Factory \u2013 built 1963<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristandc.com/economyfishing.php|title=Tristan Fishing|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>\n* Park 61 \u2013 volcanic park site\n\n==Notable people== \n*[[Conrad Glass]], police officer\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tristandc.com/settlement.php Description of the settlement]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170106201949/http://members.virtualtourist.com/m/28be5/1075/9/ Tourism Information (Archived)]\n\n{{Tristan da Cunha}}\n{{Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha}}\n\n{{coord|37|04|S|12|19|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1816]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]]\n[[Category:1816 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1816 establishments in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Edinburgh of the Seven Seas\n|other_name             = <small>\"The Settlement\"</small>\n|image_skyline          = Tristan da Cunha4.jpg\n|imagesize              = 250px\n|image_caption          = Edinburgh of the Seven Seas\n|image_map              = {{Infobox mapframe|zoom=10}}\n|map_caption            = Location on [[Tristan da Cunha]]\n|subdivision_type       = [[Sovereign state]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} United Kingdom\n|subdivision_type1      = [[British overseas territory]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{Flag|Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha}}\n|subdivision_type2      = Island\n|subdivision_name2      = {{Flag|Tristan da Cunha}}\n|established_title      = First inhabited\n|established_date       = 1816\n|established_title1     = Named\n|established_date1      = 1867\n|named_for              = [[Alfred of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha|Alfred, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n|founder                = William Glass ([[British Army]])\n|seat_type              = Capital of\n|seat                   = Tristan da Cunha\n|coordinates            = {{coord|37|4|2.2|S|12|18|36|W|region:SH_type:city(264)|display=inline}}\n|population_as_of       = January 2020\n|population_total       = 266\n|timezone1              = GMT\n|utc_offset1            = +0\n|area_code              = +44\n}}\n[[File:Edinburgh of the Seven Seas map.svg|thumb|250px|Map of Edinburgh of the Seven Seas (known locally as \u201cThe Settlement\u201d)]]\n\n'''Edinburgh of the Seven Seas''' is the main settlement of the island of [[Tristan da Cunha]], in [[Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha]], an overseas territory of the United Kingdom, in the South Atlantic Ocean. Locally, it is always referred to as The Settlement or The Village.<ref>[http://www.saint.fm/independent/20110325.pdf Saint Helena Independent] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720172747/http://www.saint.fm/independent/20110325.pdf |date=20 July 2011 }} 25 March 2011 p. 3</ref>\n\nEdinburgh of the Seven Seas is regarded as the most remote permanent settlement on Earth, being {{convert|2173|km}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristandc.com/settlement.php|title=Tristan da Cunha Settlement of Edinburgh of the Seven Seas|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref> from the nearest other human settlement, on [[Saint Helena]].\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of Tristan da Cunha}}\n\nThe settlement was founded on the island of Tristan da Cunha in 1816 by a Sergeant Glass from the Borders of Scotland{{Citation needed|date=February 2009}} after the UK annexed Tristan da Cunha. A military garrison was maintained on the islands as a guard against any French attempts to rescue [[Napoleon]], who was imprisoned on [[Saint Helena]]. The military garrison remained until the end of [[World War II]].\n\nIt is named after [[Alfred of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha|Prince Alfred, Duke of Edinburgh]], the second son of [[Queen Victoria]], in honour of his visit to the island in 1867.<ref>Courtney, Nicholas (2004). The Queen's Stamps. {{ISBN|0-413-77228-4}}, page 28. The visit took place during the [[circumnavigation]] the Duke of Edinburgh did while commanding HMS ''Galatea''. Tristan da Cunha post office issued four stamps in 1967 to celebrate the centenary of this visit.</ref>\n\nEdinburgh of the Seven Seas is the only major settlement of Tristan da Cunha, and contains a small port, the Administrator's residence, and the post office. It was damaged in a volcanic eruption on the island in 1961, which forced the entire population to abandon the settlement and evacuate to [[Calshot]], Hampshire in the UK. The eruption destroyed the settlement's [[Tristan rock lobster|crayfish]] factory.\n\nAfter the return of most of the islanders in 1963, the settlement was rebuilt. The harbour at Edinburgh was named Calshot Harbour, after their temporary home during the eruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tristandc.com/harbour.php|title=Tristan da Cunha's Calshot Harbour|publisher=|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n===Climate===\nThe archipelago has a wet [[oceanic climate]] under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen system]] with mild temperatures, but consistent moderate to heavy rainfall and very limited sunshine, due to the persistent westerly winds. Under the [[Trewartha climate classification|Trewartha classification]], Tristan da Cunha is a [[humid subtropical climate]] due to the lack of cold weather. The number of rainy days is comparable to the [[Aleutian Islands]] at a much higher latitude in the northern hemisphere, while sunshine hours are comparable to [[Juneau, Alaska]], 20\u00b0 farther from the equator. Frost is unknown below elevations of {{convert|500|m|ft|-2}} and summer temperatures are similarly mild, never reaching {{convert|25|C|F|0}}. [[Sandy Point, Tristan da Cunha|Sandy Point]] on the east coast is reputed to be the warmest and driest place on the island, being in the lee of the [[prevailing wind]]s.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Tristan da Cunha\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 23.7\n|Feb record high C = 24.4\n|Mar record high C = 24.4\n|Apr record high C = 22.4\n|May record high C = 20.3\n|Jun record high C = 18.7\n|Jul record high C = 17.8\n|Aug record high C = 17.3\n|Sep record high C = 17.1\n|Oct record high C = 18.4\n|Nov record high C = 22.4\n|Dec record high C = 21.8\n|year record high C = 24.4\n|Jan high C = 20.4\n|Feb high C = 21.2\n|Mar high C = 20.5\n|Apr high C = 18.9\n|May high C = 16.9\n|Jun high C = 15.3\n|Jul high C = 14.4\n|Aug high C = 14.2\n|Sep high C = 14.3\n|Oct high C = 15.4\n|Nov high C = 17.0\n|Dec high C = 18.9\n|y